+**Function-LEN budget (load-bearing per the Tier-1 gate).**
+
+- `build_router(...)` — ~15–30 LOC across all router modules
+  (one `router.<method>("path")(_handler(deps))` line per route +
+  prefix declaration).
+- Each `_<route>(deps)` closure factory — ~5 LOC of wrapper + the
+  inner `handler` body. FastAPI introspects the **inner**
+  `handler`'s signature for body / query / header extraction; the
+  outer factory is a transparent closure wrapper. The complexity
+  gate measures the outer factory function AND the nested inner
+  `handler` as separate `ast.FunctionDef` nodes; each is
+  independently measured against the 100-LEN / 20-CC thresholds.
+- Inner `handler` bodies — ~15–30 LOC each (matches current per-
+  route SLOC).
+
+The wave-1 PR explicitly runs `python3 scripts/check-complexity.py`
+against the new `routers/tasks.py` AND `server.py` to confirm no
+function in either is over threshold. Subsequent waves do the same.
+
+**Why closure factories rather than method-on-class or
+`functools.partial`.**
+
+- Methods on a class (e.g., `class TasksRouter:` with `async def
+  create_task(self, ...)`) work but introduce `self` in the
+  handler signature, which FastAPI does NOT introspect for body
+  / query / header parameters — `self` is treated as an unknown
+  required parameter and the route 422s on every request. Avoid.
+- `functools.partial(handler, deps=deps)` collapses the inner
+  signature in a way that breaks FastAPI's `Body(...)` / `Header(...)`
+  / `Query(...)` defaults binding (the partial's `__signature__`
+  becomes the raw underlying function's signature, missing the
+  default-marker objects). Avoid.
+- Closure factory (the shape above) is what FastAPI's own docs
+  recommend for parameterized dependency injection without
+  `Depends(...)`. The inner `handler` retains its declared
+  signature; the closure captures `deps` via lexical scope.
+
