-### 7.1 Path-parameter resolution order
+### 7.1 Path-parameter resolution order — non-issue under default scoping
 
-FastAPI's route matching iterates registration order for routes
-that share a path-parameter prefix. The current `make_app`
-registers `GET /v0/experiments/{id}` at line 1425 — AFTER all the
-more-specific `/v0/experiments/{id}/<sub>` routes (tasks, ideas,
-…). The post-F-3 `app.include_router(...)` order in `make_app`
-(Decision 5) preserves this by listing `experiment` AFTER all the
-sub-resource routers. **Test added in §6.2 locks this in.**
+FastAPI / Starlette path parameters default to **single-segment**
+matching: `{experiment_id}` matches one segment with no slashes.
+So `GET /v0/experiments/{experiment_id}` matches **only**
+`/v0/experiments/foo` and not `/v0/experiments/foo/anything`.
+Every existing route has a unique fully-qualified path; there is
+no shadowing today.
 
-If a future change adds a new sub-resource router and forgets to
-add it BEFORE `experiment`, the `GET /v0/experiments/{id}` route
-shadows it. The test in §6.2 catches the canonical case (tasks);
-new resources need similar coverage when added.
+This means `app.include_router(...)` order is a stylistic choice,
+not a correctness invariant. Decision 5 chooses to match the
+current file's registration order anyway, under the no-behavior-
+change discipline. Decision 5a's split of the experiment routes
+into `experiment_lifecycle` + `experiment_read` is the
+consequence of that choice — the split exists to let the include
+order match the file exactly, not because order is technically
+required.
 
+**Where ordering WOULD matter (forward-looking).** If a future
+amendment introduces a route with a greedy path parameter
+(`{path:path}`, which DOES match multi-segment paths), or if two
+routes with the same method share a path-segment-equivalent
+pattern, ordering becomes load-bearing. The §6.2 regression test
+(`test_path_segment_scoping_no_shadow`) pins the current
+assumption so a future change that breaks it fails loudly.
+
